K-M-S in practice, across S3, E-B-S, and R-D-S. Three integrations that come up constantly.

Start with S3, which has four server-side encryption modes. S-S-E-dash-S3 uses A-W-S managed keys with no K-M-S involved; it's the default, the cheapest, and gives no per-request audit trail. S-S-E-dash-K-M-S uses a K-M-S key, managed or a C-M-K, and here every GET triggers a K-M-S Decrypt call that's logged in CloudTrail. S-S-E-dash-C means you supply the key on every request; A-W-S encrypts and decrypts but never stores your key. And client-side means the application encrypts before upload, so A-W-S never sees the plaintext at all.

The big gotcha with S-S-E-dash-K-M-S is that every single S3 GET calls K-M-S to decrypt. At high request rates that can hit the per-region K-M-S rate limit, which is somewhere between five-thousand-five-hundred and thirty-thousand requests a second depending on region. The fix is S3 Bucket Keys; S3 derives a short-lived bucket-level data key from K-M-S and reuses it across many objects, which dramatically cuts K-M-S A-P-I calls. Enable bucket keys whenever you use S-S-E-dash-K-M-S at scale.

E-B-S encryption is chosen at volume creation, either the a-w-s-slash-e-b-s key or a C-M-K, and it covers data at rest, snapshots, and disk I-O. You cannot encrypt an existing unencrypted volume in place; you snapshot it, copy the snapshot with encryption enabled, and restore. Turn on account-level default encryption so every new volume is encrypted automatically. R-D-S encryption works the same way, set at creation, covering the instance, automated backups, snapshots, and read replicas, and again you can't encrypt an existing unencrypted instance directly, you snapshot, copy encrypted, and restore. T-L-S protects data in transit to the database; K-M-S protects it at rest.

The through-line for the exam: K-M-S is chosen at resource-creation time, it encrypts at rest transparently, and for storage it is very hard to add after the fact.
